<p><b>Thales of Miletus</b> (<span lang="grc" xml:lang="grc">Θαλῆς ὁ Μιλήσιος</span> (pronounced <span title="Pronunciation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA_for_English" title="Wikipedia:IPA for English">/ˈθeɪliːz/</a></span> or "THEH-leez") , ca. 624 BC–ca. 546 BC), was a <a href="/wiki/Pre-Socratic_philosophy" title="Pre-Socratic philosophy">pre-Socratic</a> <a href="/wiki/Greek_philosophy" title="Greek philosophy">Greek philosopher</a> from <a href="/wiki/Miletus" title="Miletus">Miletus</a> in <a href="/wiki/Asia_Minor" title="Asia Minor" class="mw-redirect">Asia Minor</a>, and one of the <a href="/wiki/Seven_Sages_of_Greece" title="Seven Sages of Greece">Seven Sages of Greece</a>. Many, most notably Aristotle, regard him as the first philosopher in the <a href="/wiki/Greek_philosophy" title="Greek philosophy">Greek tradition</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> According to <a href="/wiki/Bertrand_Russell" title="Bertrand Russell">Bertrand Russell</a>, "Philosophy begins with Thales."<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
